h3. Expected behaviour

By default, when Agent's select to comment on a Service Desk ticket, there is a pre-populated message with the Reporter's name, as well as the user that is responding as a signature:

{noformat}
Hi <reporter>,

– <agent>
{noformat}

h3. Current Behaviour

On versions 3.2, 3.2.1 and 3.2.2 this feature is not present in JIRA. The pre-populated message is not present on the comments made by Agents. I tested this on a 3.1.9 version and it still works there.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Service Desk Server*. Using *JIRA Service Desk Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-4332].
  {panel}

In JIRA 7 customer can use the *Upgrade* button to upgrade JIRA Service Desk application directly from *JIRA Administration > Applications > Versions & licenses*.
However if the a new major version of JIRA Service Desk is released (for example JSD 3.2.0) since it's not compatible with the previous major version of JIRA (for example JIRA 7.1) user will not be able to see the upgrade button for the latest version of JSD.
It would be nice if we can display a message to inform the customer that in order to upgrade to the latest version of JSD application, customer should upgrade the JIRA first.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Service Desk Server*. Using *JIRA Service Desk Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-4330].
  {panel}

If you have a Service Desk ticket with many comments, it seems odd to have the "Comment" button at the top of the page scroll you all the way down to the bottom of the page to add the comment.

First of all, if you have your comments sorted in reverse order, so more recent comments are on top, the placement of the "Add comment" is in the wrong place.

I think the interface would work better if clicking on the "Comment" button opened a dialog box, similar to the "Create Issue" button's dialog.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Service Desk Server*. Using *JIRA Service Desk Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-4329].
  {panel}

I don't wont my JSD agents to access other than their own assigned issues, but the JSD overrides the browse project permissions.

How can I set up a issue security level to handle this in the service desk ?

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Service Desk Server*. Using *JIRA Service Desk Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-4326].
  {panel}

When discussing issues with customers using service desk, it not possible for the customer to sort their requests by key for example. The default sort is by latest update. When discussing issue over the phone and updating concurrently, the list gets resorted all the time.

It would be extremely useful when you could sort using the headers in the request list.

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
  *NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Service Desk Server*. Using *JIRA Service Desk Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JSDCLOUD-4319].
  {panel}

While the announcement functionality recently added to Service Desk is nice, our team was looking at how to best add time relevant information to the knowledge base. For example, outage notifications could be an announcement, but that does involve extra steps and a different process from one agents are already familiar with: updating the Service Desk Knowledge Base (Linked Confluence space.) 

The Confluence blog feature seems like a perfect solution for information that is important today or this week, but won't be relevant in the near future. A check boxe for "Show in Customer Portal" and a date/time picker for "Remove from Customer Portal At" would be ideal.

